How do environmental factors impact educational attainment in English towns?

Zach, Xinyu, Rishi,

2025-03-07


Introduction

Our research question below aims to understand how environmental factors impact educational success in english towns:

What are the strongest environmental predictors of educational success?

It is very important to understand the relationship between environmental factors at youth, and educational attainment, because doing so allows us to better support the educational success of younger generations. The environmental factors collected in this data set, some of which include location, income, and population density, all contribute to a child’s learning environment. Understanding how these factors correlate, allows us to device strategies that ensure every child has the resources and support needed to succeed academically, and thus have better chances at a comfortable life.

Data Source

The data set we chose comes from the UK Office of National Statistics for the purpose of analyzing factors that contribute to children and young people’s higher academic achievements in smaller towns versus larger towns: https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/tree/main/data/2024/2024-01-23#english_educationcsv

To gather this data, the sample was selected from pupils who sat their GCSEs in the 2012 to 2013 school year, using Longitudinal Education Outcomes collected by the Department for Education. The data compares educational attainment in English towns at primary school level (Key Stage 2) in the 2007 to 2008 school year, attainment at GSCE level in the 2012 to 2013 school year, qualifications attained by age 18 (school year 2014 to 2015), and qualifications attained by age 22 (school year 2018 to 2019).

Worflow

We will be proposing three models for the training split of our english_education data, and then evaluating them on the testing split.

Our response variable will be education_score, which is based on attainment levels of the 2012/13 Key stage 4 cohort. The explanatory variables we will be considering are; key_stage_2_attainment_school_year_2007_to_2008, activity_at_age_19_out_of_work, coastal, level_2_at_age_18, level_3_at_age_18, income_lvl, ttwa_classification, key_stage_4_attainment_school_year_2012_to_2013, and highest_level_qualification_achieved_b_age_22_average_score, which are described in the code book below.

We will be recoding two variables with mutate(), income_flag and ttwa_clasification, to create income_lvl and ttwa_reclass. This way, we can group an individual’s income_flag classification into affluent or non-affluent, and group an individuals travel-to-work area classification into urban or rural.

We will be re-coding income_flag (which is used to describe towns as lower income deprivation, mid income deprivation or higher income deprivation) into income_lvl, in order to simplify observation locations into affluent or non-affluent.


Code Book
variable class description
education_score numeric Town/city education score based on attainment levels of the 2012/13 Key stage 4 cohort.
activity_at_age_19_out_of_work numeric Proportion of the town/city’s 2012/13 key stage 4 cohort claiming out-of-work benefits at age 19.
key_stage_2_attainment_school_year_2007_to_2008 numeric Proportion of pupils that achieved level 4 or above (expected level) in key stage 2 in English and Maths in the 2007 to 2008 school year.
coastal character Variable used to describe towns as coastal or non-coastal.
level_2_at_age_18 numeric Proportion of the town/city’s 2012/13 key stage 4 cohort that achieved level 2 qualifications at 18.
level_3_at_age_18 numeric Proportion of the town/city’s 2012/13 key stage 4 cohort that achieved level 3 qualifications at 18.
income_lvl character Mutated column based on income_flag. Classifies neighborhood as affluent or not.
income_flag character Variable used to describe towns as lower income deprivation, mid income deprivation or higher income deprivation.
highest_level_qualification_achieved_b_age_22_average_score numeric Town/city highest qualification average score based on highest levels of qualifications achieved of the 2012/13 KS4 cohort.
key_stage_4_attainment_school_year_2012_to_2013 numeric Proportion of pupils that achieved 5 GCSE or more, including English and Maths, with grades A*-C in the 2012 to 2013 school year.
ttwa_classification character Travel to work area classification.
ttwa_reclass character Mutated column based on ttwa_classification. Classifies observation as residing within urban areas or rural.

Section 3 - Results

The best model among our three proposals is Rishi’s (model_rishi), which achieved the highest adjusted R squared of 0.94 and the lowest RMSE of 0.73. His model effectively combines prior knowledge about the association between education_score and education levels, grades from the 2012-13 school year, and commuting characteristics of an individual’s location, to create a model that draws on variables that are both practical to college and easy to interpret. This model demonstrates that the best predictors of education_score are the proportion of GCSEs completed with grades A*-C in 2012-13, the travel-to-work area where an individual resides, and the average level of formal education achieved by age 22.

Conclusion

In the larger context of how environmental factors impact educational attainment in English towns and our research question focusing on the strongest predictors, we have found that the best predictor of education_score is an individual’s average level of qualifications by age 22, followed by their key stage 4 attainment in the school year 2012-13 and travel-to-work area classification (rural or urban). Individuals who have achieved higher levels of educational credentials, like a bachelor’s degree, are much more likely to have high education scores. The same applies to an individual’s key stage 4 attainment in the years 2012-13. Having a larger proportion of GCSE grades that fall within A-C letter grades result in a higher education score. Lastly, when it comes to travel-to-work area classification, education score tends to decrease for individuals residing in urban areas rather than rural.
